(16, 1, '2025-05-05 17:27:32', '2025-05-05 17:27:32', '<h4 data-start=\"791\" data-end=\"1283\"><strong data-start=\"791\" data-end=\"825\">Introduction to Conceptual Art</strong></h4>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"791\" data-end=\"1283\">\r\nConceptual art emerged in the 1960s as a reaction against the traditional forms of artistic expression, emphasizing the intellectual engagement of the viewer over aesthetic experience. Pioneers like Marcel Duchamp and Sol LeWitt questioned the very nature of art itself, suggesting that an idea could be as significant as a physical object. The art world, once dominated by traditional painting and sculpture, began to explore new ways of engaging the mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 data-start=\"1285\" data-end=\"1810\"><strong data-start=\"1285\" data-end=\"1319\">The Role of Language and Ideas</strong></h4>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"1285\" data-end=\"1810\">\r\nOne of the core features of conceptual art is the use of language and text to convey meaning. Artists often employ written instructions, diagrams, or even conceptual frameworks that allow the viewer to interpret the work on an intellectual level. This challenges the viewer’s expectations and moves beyond the purely visual experience of art. For example, artists like Joseph Kosuth used dictionary definitions to confront the viewer with fundamental questions about perception and reality.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"2264\"><strong data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"1856\">Conceptual Art in the Contemporary World</strong></h4>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"2264\">\r\nToday, conceptual art continues to influence a wide array of artistic practices. Artists have embraced the idea that art is an ongoing dialogue between the creator, the viewer, and the context in which it exists. In a world increasingly dominated by digital culture and virtual spaces, the conceptual approach remains a powerful tool for exploring new ideas about identity, technology, and human experience.</p>', 'The Evolution of Conceptual Art: Breaking Boundaries of Traditional Art', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-evolution-of-conceptual-art-breaking-boundaries-of-traditional-art', '', '', '2025-05-06 04:54:30', '2025-05-06 04:54:30', '', 0, 'http://localhost/scribblenews/?p=16', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(17, 1, '2025-05-05 17:27:32', '2025-05-05 17:27:32', '<p class=\"\" data-start=\"791\" data-end=\"1283\"><strong data-start=\"791\" data-end=\"825\">Introduction to Conceptual Art</strong>\r\nConceptual art emerged in the 1960s as a reaction against the traditional forms of artistic expression, emphasizing the intellectual engagement of the viewer over aesthetic experience. Pioneers like Marcel Duchamp and Sol LeWitt questioned the very nature of art itself, suggesting that an idea could be as significant as a physical object. The art world, once dominated by traditional painting and sculpture, began to explore new ways of engaging the mind.</p>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"1285\" data-end=\"1810\"><strong data-start=\"1285\" data-end=\"1319\">The Role of Language and Ideas</strong>\r\nOne of the core features of conceptual art is the use of language and text to convey meaning. Artists often employ written instructions, diagrams, or even conceptual frameworks that allow the viewer to interpret the work on an intellectual level. This challenges the viewer’s expectations and moves beyond the purely visual experience of art. For example, artists like Joseph Kosuth used dictionary definitions to confront the viewer with fundamental questions about perception and reality.</p>\r\n<p class=\"\" data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"2264\"><strong data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"1856\">Conceptual Art in the Contemporary World</strong>\r\nToday, conceptual art continues to influence a wide array of artistic practices. Artists have embraced the idea that art is an ongoing dialogue between the creator, the viewer, and the context in which it exists. In a world increasingly dominated by digital culture and virtual spaces, the conceptual approach remains a powerful tool for exploring new ideas about identity, technology, and human experience.</p>', 'The Evolution of Conceptual Art: Breaking Boundaries of Traditional Art', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-05-05 17:27:32', '2025-05-05 17:27:32', '', 16, 'http://localhost/scribblenews/?p=17', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
